metadata.name: Alienpillars #11
metadata.description:
"A rare type of bug that supposedly arrived on a cargo ship is destroying crops on planet Uctumi, in the binary system of Extronium. A wide variety of very resistant subspecies has mutated and it is necessary to study and identify all of them to obtain a gen-activated pesticide that will work on all of their variations. The pest department of the Uctumi central government is working hard on it, and they say that these strange critters are probably related to similar species that inhabited the planet Earth of the Solar system a long time ago and have spread over the galaxy."

My second piece using the p5.js raymarcher I wrote. The drawing is made of circles and lines based on the 3D data. I wanted to try something hairy as it's easy to draw lines aligned to the surface normal with this method. I also used a shader for the frame and the glitchy/sketch features.

Features 

body color: green-red-purple-yellow-blue-black
body tone: dark-light
spots color: orange-green-blue-yellow-white
hair tips: yes-no
hair #1: short-medium-long
hair #2: short-medium-long
head size: small-medium-large
head shape: long-spherical-wide
glitchy mode: 10% chance
sketch mode: 9% chance

metadata.name: HOWL.camera #31
metadata.description:
Created with the permission and endorsement of Allen Ginsberg's estate, enabled by theVERSEverse, this work channels Ginsberg's iconic poem HOWL through a dynamic ASCII lens.

Written by Ross Goodwin using 54 of Ginsberg's original photographs and a Markov language model of HOWL in vanilla JS. Each edition shifts from the minter's chosen photograph after 10 seconds into pure ASCII noise, eventually devolving into chaotic Markov fragments.

60% of mint and royalty proceeds will be donated to benefit victims of the recent Los Angeles fires.

https://howl.camera

metadata.name: Ichigo #265
metadata.description:
This generator is named 'Ichigo' (è‹º/ ã„ã¡ã”), the Japanese word for 'strawberry'. 

Seeing each iteration from a suitable distance, small dots (to me, reminiscent of strawberry seeds) overlay different sequences of geometric repetitions, implying a sense of texture, grittiness and irregularity. 

By looking closer however, it becomes apparent to the viewer that the majority of the composition is in fact government by orderly elements, in this case grids of dots. 

This discovery invites the viewer to consider the output in front of them at different levels, near and far. At what point do you feel the dots begin to dissolve into a texture? When do you stop noticing the dots and instead begin to perceive the overall composition?

These questions are posed in a similar fashion as with meditation; at what point does something become something else? When does an in-breath become an out-breath and vice versa? 

Contemplation on simple questions like these can open a small portal into stillness and mindfulness by taking time to slowly observe our responses. 

23 palettes are included, each named after different areas of Tokyo. 

Press 'S' to download a full size 6000px x 6000px PNG output. 

As always, much gratitude and enjoy your piece.

metadata.name: glory hole$ #330
metadata.description:
our consciousness as humans can be distilled into a crudely fashioned hole at an abandoned dave & busters and the meditative state that is endured while sitting on a neglected toilet praying for the sound of disrupted waters. glory holes embody anonymity and pleasure for pleasure's sake. they are creations that cannot be destroyed, as they exist in the memories of anyone who uses or witnesses. many speculate that the carving of the hole is the purest form of human ingenuity and the desire to explore the unknown. formerly limited to the physical space. these glory holes transcend space and time. and exist in that same unknown that tempts us all. legalize ground beef. create nothing. consume everything.

HUGE thank you to @PureSpider for the layered PNG template, this dream would not have been realized without you friend.

metadata.name: WTBS: Wearable #1 (cap edition) #1
metadata.description:
The Waiting is over. Itâ€™s actually happening. Weâ€™ve teased, hinted, and honestly YEARNED for this release. We hope you enjoy.

WTBS: Wearable #1 (cap edition) is a celebration of the 3rd anniversary of the Waiting To Be Signed Podcast. We mark this milestone in collaboration with artist Anna Lucia and are extremely pleased to bring you these one-of-a-kind generative caps. Each NFT in this series is an animated digital artwork which contains the embroidery design for a unique cap. When you obtain an NFT from this collection, youâ€™re not only collecting digital art, you can also redeem a cap featuring the very design! 

Get your cap: 

Anna Lucia has curated a full collection using fx(hash)â€™s params function. At the time of sale, all NFTs will have already been minted by Anna Lucia & ready for sale. You can acquire your preferred design by placing an offer of $75 or more (in TEZ equivalent), which will be accepted by Anna. This price includes the NFT & cap but excludes shipping. Cap redemption will be handled via Artfora.com. 
If you are not buying the cap directly from Anna Luciaâ€™s wallet (tz1M7dt8sWC64ZXkmiWbttVCtgFrFU6Do9x9), please view the collection on Artfora to check whether the cap has already been redeemed or not. 

Controls:

The NFT itself showcases the dynamic, animated generative design. Use the interactive controls to explore variations and preview how your chosen design will look on the embroidered cap. There are two colors cap, black and desert beige, represented by the background color and reflected in the mock-up. 

A -> Toggle between animated view and cap mock-up
D -> Download the embroidery file 
E -> Detailed view of embroidery design 
R -> Record and download a .zip file of 300 frames

On mobile only the digital animated view is available. 

This work is created with p5.js and stitch.js.

metadata.name: Ã‰tudes #255
metadata.description:
- Click to start the sound - 

â€˜Ã‰tudesâ€™ is a series of generative notation accompanied with sound.

â€˜Ã‰tudesâ€™ is the first series of the â€˜Notationsâ€™ collection. â€˜Notationsâ€™ will explore various notation techniques around the world and will use different sonification techniques and generative music algorithms.

In this series, a sonification process has been used to generate sound.

Some articulations or accidentals intentionally exist due to aesthetic preferences. For example there are some musically meaningless things like vibrato on a piano or a coda sign on a motif. And some notes will play the same pitch (even if they appear apart from one another) depending on the chosen scale.

Sonification tends to work better after 2nd (or even 3rd) play. Some minor audio bugs might occur. 

There is a major but a rare bug which we intentionally kept in; it plays a generative piece from indicated pitches rather than just playing the motif only once.

There is a rare possibility that â€˜Ã‰tudesâ€™ can generate an â€˜electronicâ€™ result which plays with a FM synth instead of piano.

Probabilities;

- 12 root notes

 - 12 different scales

- Dynamics; pp,p,mp,mf,f,ff or none

- Dynamic changes; crescendo and diminuendo or none

- 4 different noteheads

- Several accidentals and articulations

- Vibrato might occur on some outputs

- 3 font styles

- 4 background textures
